---
// The equilibrium-lesson player (ADR-0048): the ICE table = the species ledger with the extent solved from mass
// action. Six subtypes — `weak-acid` (the pH), `buffer` (common-ion + Henderson–Hasselbalch), `weak-base` (→ pOH
// → pH via K_w), `solubility` (Ksp → molar solubility, the pure solid excluded from Q; optionally a common ion —
// the common-ion effect on the cubic), `polyprotic` (staged Kₐ, the solver run once per stage), and `titration`
// (a weak-acid/strong-base pH curve — a build-time SVG of verified points). A fully STATIC Astro component. Every
// value came from ChemKernel and was re-verified (equilibriumcheck.mjs).
const { lesson } = Astro.props;
const isKsp = lesson.subtype === "solubility";
const isCommonIon = isKsp && !!lesson.reaction.common_ion;   // the Ksp common-ion variant (a shared ion pre-loaded)
const isBase = lesson.subtype === "weak-base";
const isBuffer = lesson.subtype === "buffer";
const isPoly = lesson.subtype === "polyprotic";           // a polyprotic acid ionizing in stages (top ice = stage 1)
const isTitration = lesson.subtype === "titration";       // a weak-acid/strong-base titration curve (top ice = the initial point)
const ice = lesson.ice;

// titration → SVG geometry, computed at BUILD time (the player draws no chemistry — it plots verified points)
let tit = null;
if (isTitration) {
  const t = lesson.titration;
  const W = 640, H = 360, ml = 52, mr = 18, mt = 16, mb = 42;
  const pw = W - ml - mr, ph = H - mt - mb;
  const vmax = Math.max(...t.curve.map((p) => Number(p.volume_mL)));
  const px = (v) => ml + (Number(v) / vmax) * pw;
  const py = (p) => mt + (1 - Number(p) / 14) * ph;
  const pts = t.curve.map((p) => `${px(p.volume_mL).toFixed(1)},${py(p.pH).toFixed(1)}`).join(" ");
  const marks = [["initial", "start"], ["half_equivalence", "½-eq · pH = pKₐ"], ["equivalence", "equivalence"]].map(([k, label]) => {
    const m = t.landmarks[k];
    return { key: k, x: px(m.volume_mL), y: py(m.pH), pH: m.pH_display, v: m.volume_mL_display, label };
  });
  const phGrid = [0, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14].map((v) => ({ v, y: py(v) }));
  const step = vmax <= 30 ? 5 : 10;
  const vTicks = [];
  for (let v = 0; v <= vmax + 1e-6; v += step) vTicks.push({ v, x: px(v) });
  tit = { W, H, ml, mr, mt, mb, pw, ph, pts, marks, phGrid, vTicks, y7: py(7), vmax };
}
const rows = ice.species;
const xSym = ice.extent_symbol;                          // "x" (acid) or "s" (Ksp)
const kc = lesson.equilibrium_constant;
const res = lesson.result;

// the "cubic vs √Ksp" factor in the Ksp misconception, computed from the data rather than hardcoded (QC 2026-07-09
// C8): the naive-wrong answer treats Ksp = s², giving s = √Ksp; the correct cubic root is this many times larger.
const kspSqrtRatio = isKsp ? Math.round(Number(res.molar_solubility_M) / Math.sqrt(Number(kc.value))) : null;

// the constant symbol as HTML (K_a → Kₐ, K_sp → K_sp)
const kParts = kc.symbol.split("_");
const kHtml = `${kParts[0]}${kParts[1] ? `<sub>${kParts[1]}</sub>` : ""}`;

// symbolic change per row: ν·x, e.g. −x, +x, +2s; a pure solid (excluded) shows a dash
const SUP = { "2": "²", "3": "³", "4": "⁴" };
const changeSym = (r) => {
  if (r.in_quotient === false) return "—";
  const n = Math.abs(r.nu);
  return (r.nu < 0 ? "−" : "+") + (n === 1 ? "" : n) + xSym;
};

// generic mass-action substitution from the in-quotient rows: ∏[products]^ν / ∏[reactants]^ν
const inQ = rows.filter((r) => r.in_quotient !== false);
const term = (r) => `(${r.equilibrium_M_display})${r.nu > 1 ? (SUP[r.nu] ?? `^${r.nu}`) : ""}`;
const numer = inQ.filter((r) => r.nu > 0).map(term).join("");
const denom = inQ.filter((r) => r.nu < 0).map(term).join("");
const substitution = denom ? `${numer} / ${denom}` : numer;

// the dissolved reactant row (the un-ionized acid or base) — skips the excluded pure solvent (water). null for Ksp.
const reactantRow = !isKsp ? rows.find((r) => r.role === "reactant" && r.in_quotient !== false) : null;
// the excluded pure-condensed-phase row (a solid for Ksp, water for a weak base) — "pure liquid"/"pure solid" by phase
const excludedRow = rows.find((r) => r.in_quotient === false);
const excludedNoun = excludedRow && excludedRow.phase === "l" ? "liquid" : "solid";
const excludedFrom = isKsp ? "Ksp" : "Q";
---

<section class="player">
  <header class="head">
    <div class="badges">
      <span class="badge machine"><span class="dot"></span>ICE ledger machine-checked — every dissolved row is initial + ν·{xSym}, one extent {xSym}</span>
      <span class="badge sourced"><span class="dot"></span><Fragment set:html={kHtml} /> data-sourced ({kc.source})</span>
      <span class="badge model"><span class="dot"></span>{lesson.assumptions.length} modeling assumption{lesson.assumptions.length === 1 ? "" : "s"} (disclosed)</span>
    </div>
    <p class="scenario" set:html={lesson.scenarioHtml} />
  </header>

  <!-- the reversible reaction + the equilibrium constant it must satisfy -->
  <div class="reaction">
    <div class="rxn" set:html={lesson.reaction.latexHtml} />
    <div class="ka">
      <span class="expr" set:html={kc.expressionHtml} />
      <span class="eq">=</span>
      <span class="kaval">{kc.valueSci}</span>
      <span class="kalabel">at 25 °C</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- the ICE table: Initial → Change → Equilibrium. This IS the species ledger (c = c₀ + ν·{xSym}) in concentrations. -->
  <div class="tablewrap">
    <table class="ice">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Species</th>
          <th class="num">Initial (M)</th>
          <th class="num">Change (M)</th>
          <th class="num">Equilibrium (M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {rows.map((r) => (
          <tr class={r.in_quotient === false ? "solid" : ""}>
            <td class="sym"><span set:html={r.symbolHtml} /> <span class="phase">({r.phase})</span>{r.in_quotient === false && <span class="excluded">pure {excludedNoun} · excluded from {excludedFrom}</span>}</td>
            <td class="num">{r.in_quotient === false ? "—" : r.initial_M}</td>
            <td class="num change"><span class="csym">{changeSym(r)}</span></td>
            <td class="num eqm">{r.in_quotient === false ? "—" : r.equilibrium_M_display}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p class="ledger-note">
    <span class="badge machine tiny"><span class="dot"></span>machine-checked</span>
    The Change row is <strong>ν·{xSym}</strong> — the very same extent ledger <span class="mono">c<sub>i</sub> = c<sub>i,0</sub> + ν<sub>i</sub>·{xSym}</span>
    as any reaction. {isKsp ? "The pure solid has activity 1, so it never enters the equilibrium expression."
      : isBase ? "Water is the pure solvent (activity 1), so it never enters the equilibrium expression."
      : isPoly ? `This is the first of ${res.proton_count} ionizations — the one that releases nearly all of the H⁺.`
      : isTitration ? "This is the starting solution, before any base is added — the leftmost point of the curve below."
      : "What differs is only where the extent stops."}
  </p>

  <!-- the payoff: the extent that makes the reaction quotient equal K (the reversible-extent solve) -->
  <div class="proof massaction">
    <div class="proof-head">
      <span class="badge machine"><span class="dot"></span>Mass action</span>
      <strong>{xSym} = {ice.extent_M_display} {isKsp ? "M — the molar solubility, where" : isBase ? "M = [OH⁻], the extent where" : "M — the extent where"} Q = <Fragment set:html={kHtml} />.</strong>
    </div>
    <p class="subst">
      <span class="expr" set:html={kc.expressionHtml} />
      <span class="eq">=</span>
      <span class="nums mono">{substitution}</span>
      <span class="eq">=</span>
      <span class="kaval">{lesson.mass_action.quotientSci}</span>
      <span class="eq">= <Fragment set:html={kHtml} /> ✓</span>
    </p>
    <p class="resid">Put the committed equilibrium concentrations back in and the quotient reproduces <Fragment set:html={kHtml} /> to
      within {lesson.mass_action.residualSci} — the solver found the extent{isKsp ? " (a cubic — solved numerically, not by a formula)" : ""}, and an independent check re-solves it and agrees.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- titration: the pH curve (a build-time SVG of verified points — the ledger marched as titrant is added) -->
  {isTitration && tit && (
    <div class="titration">
      <div class="proof-head">
        <span class="badge machine"><span class="dot"></span>The titration curve</span>
        <strong>Every point is the ICE re-solved — the ledger marched as <span set:html={lesson.titration.titrantPretty} /> is added.</strong>
      </div>
      <p class="neut">The base drives the neutralization <span class="expr" set:html={lesson.titration.neutralizationHtml} />, but the pH at every drop is still set by the acid equilibrium above.</p>
      <div class="tablewrap">
        <svg viewBox={`0 0 ${tit.W} ${tit.H}`} class="curve" role="img" aria-label="Titration curve: pH versus added base volume">
          {tit.phGrid.map((g) => (
            <Fragment>
              <line x1={tit.ml} y1={g.y} x2={tit.W - tit.mr} y2={g.y} class={g.v === 7 ? "grid ph7" : "grid"} />
              <text x={tit.ml - 8} y={g.y + 4} class="axlabel" text-anchor="end">{g.v}</text>
            </Fragment>
          ))}
          {tit.vTicks.map((tk) => (
            <Fragment>
              <line x1={tk.x} y1={tit.mt} x2={tk.x} y2={tit.H - tit.mb} class="gridv" />
              <text x={tk.x} y={tit.H - tit.mb + 18} class="axlabel" text-anchor="middle">{tk.v}</text>
            </Fragment>
          ))}
          <text x={(tit.ml + tit.W - tit.mr) / 2} y={tit.H - 6} class="axtitle" text-anchor="middle">mL of base added</text>
          <text x={15} y={(tit.mt + tit.H - tit.mb) / 2} class="axtitle" text-anchor="middle" transform={`rotate(-90 15 ${(tit.mt + tit.H - tit.mb) / 2})`}>pH</text>
          <polyline points={tit.pts} class="curveline" fill="none" />
          {tit.marks.map((m) => (
            <Fragment>
              <circle cx={m.x} cy={m.y} r="4.5" class={`mark ${m.key}`} />
              <text x={m.x + (m.key === "equivalence" ? -9 : 9)} y={m.y - 9} class="marklabel" text-anchor={m.key === "equivalence" ? "end" : "start"}>{m.label}</text>
            </Fragment>
          ))}
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div class="landmarks">
        {tit.marks.map((m) => (
          <div class={`lm ${m.key}`}>
            <span class="lm-k">{m.label}</span>
            <span class="lm-v">pH {m.pH}</span>
            <span class="lm-sub">at {m.v} mL</span>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
      <p class="hhnote">
        <span class="badge machine tiny"><span class="dot"></span>Read the curve</span>
        The gentle stretch is the <strong>buffer</strong> region — flattest at <strong>{lesson.titration.half_equivalence_volume_mL_display} mL</strong>
        (half the acid neutralized), where <strong>pH ≈ pK<sub>a</sub> = {lesson.titration.pKa_display}</strong> — the buffer
        identity, exact under Henderson–Hasselbalch; the exact solve gives {res.pH_half_equivalence_display}, a hair above pK<sub>a</sub>
        because a little more acid ionizes (the small gap is just rounding either side of their shared value). The steep jump is the
        {" "}<strong>equivalence point</strong> at <strong>{lesson.titration.equivalence_volume_mL_display} mL</strong>: all the acid has become
        {" "}<span set:html={lesson.reaction.conjugateBasePretty} /> — a weak base — so the pH there is <strong>{res.pH_equivalence_display}</strong>, well above 7.
      </p>
    </div>
  )}

  <!-- the reported results -->
  {isKsp ? (
    <div class="results">
      <div class="card headline">
        <span class="k">molar solubility</span>
        <span class="v big">{res.molar_solubility_M_display} M</span>
        <span class="sub">of {lesson.reaction.saltPretty} dissolves</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="k">solubility</span>
        <span class="v">{res.solubility_g_per_L_display} g/L</span>
        <span class="sub">= {xSym} × {res.molar_mass_g_per_mol} g/mol</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="k">saturated ions</span>
        <span class="v small">{inQ.map((r) => `[${r.idPretty}] = ${r.equilibrium_M_display}`).join(" · ")}</span>
        <span class="sub">M at equilibrium</span>
      </div>
      {isCommonIon && (
        <div class="card">
          <span class="k">vs. pure water</span>
          <span class="v">{res.suppression_factor_display}× less</span>
          <span class="sub">{res.molar_solubility_pure_water_M_display} M → {res.molar_solubility_M_display} M</span>
        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  ) : isBase ? (
    <div class="results">
      <div class="card">
        <span class="k">[OH<sup>−</sup>]</span>
        <span class="v">{res.hydroxide_M_display} M</span>
        <span class="sub">{res.percent_ionization_display}% of the base ionized</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="k">pOH</span>
        <span class="v">{res.pOH_display}</span>
        <span class="sub">= −log<sub>10</sub>[OH<sup>−</sup>]</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card headline">
        <span class="k">pH</span>
        <span class="v big">{res.pH_display}</span>
        <span class="sub">= 14.00 − pOH</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  ) : isBuffer ? (
    <div class="results">
      <div class="card headline">
        <span class="k">pH</span>
        <span class="v big">{res.pH_display}</span>
        <span class="sub">≈ pK<sub>a</sub> = {res.pKa_display}</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="k">buffer ratio [A<sup>−</sup>]/[HA]</span>
        <span class="v">{res.buffer_ratio_display}</span>
        <span class="sub">at equilibrium</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="k">acid ionized</span>
        <span class="v">{res.percent_ionization_display}%</span>
        <span class="sub">[H<sup>+</sup>] = {res.hydronium_M_display} M</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  ) : isPoly ? (
    <div class="results">
      <div class="card headline">
        <span class="k">pH</span>
        <span class="v big">{res.pH_display}</span>
        <span class="sub">set almost entirely by the first ionization</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="k">[H<sup>+</sup>]</span>
        <span class="v">{res.hydronium_M_display} M</span>
        <span class="sub">{res.percent_ionization_display}% of the 1st proton ionizes</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="k">ionizes in</span>
        <span class="v">{res.proton_count} stages</span>
        <span class="sub">K<sub>a1</sub> ≫ K<sub>a2</sub> ≫ K<sub>a3</sub></span>
      </div>
    </div>
  ) : isTitration ? (
    <div class="results">
      <div class="card">
        <span class="k">start (0 mL)</span>
        <span class="v">pH {res.pH_display}</span>
        <span class="sub">the pure weak acid</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card headline">
        <span class="k">half-equivalence</span>
        <span class="v big">pH {res.pH_half_equivalence_display}</span>
        <span class="sub">≈ pK<sub>a</sub> = {res.pKa_display}</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="k">equivalence</span>
        <span class="v">pH {res.pH_equivalence_display}</span>
        <span class="sub">basic — the acid is now a weak base</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  ) : (
    <div class="results">
      <div class="card">
        <span class="k">[H<sup>+</sup>]</span>
        <span class="v">{res.hydronium_M_display} M</span>
        <span class="sub">{res.percent_ionization_display}% of the acid ionized</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card headline">
        <span class="k">pH</span>
        <span class="v big">{res.pH_display}</span>
        <span class="sub">= −log<sub>10</sub>[H<sup>+</sup>]</span>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <span class="k">un-ionized</span>
        <span class="v">{reactantRow.equilibrium_M_display} M</span>
        <span class="sub">stays as intact {lesson.reaction.acidPretty}</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  )}

  <!-- the K_w bridge, the weak base's new move: [OH⁻] → [H⁺] → pH (SHOWN, machine-checked) -->
  {isBase && (
    <p class="kwbridge">
      <span class="badge machine tiny"><span class="dot"></span>K<sub>w</sub> bridge</span>
      The extent gives <strong>[OH<sup>−</sup>] = {res.hydroxide_M_display} M</strong>, not [H<sup>+</sup>]. Water ties them together:
      <span class="mono">[H<sup>+</sup>][OH<sup>−</sup>] = K<sub>w</sub> = {lesson.result.kwSci}</span>, so
      <span class="mono">[H<sup>+</sup>] = K<sub>w</sub>/[OH<sup>−</sup>] = {res.hydronium_M_display} M</span> and
      <strong>pH + pOH = {res.pH_display} + {res.pOH_display} = {(Number(res.pH_display) + Number(res.pOH_display)).toFixed(2)}</strong>.
    </p>
  )}

  <!-- Henderson–Hasselbalch: the mass-action law in log form (buffer only, SHOWN + machine-checked) -->
  {isBuffer && (
    <p class="hhnote">
      <span class="badge machine tiny"><span class="dot"></span>Henderson–Hasselbalch</span>
      Take −log of <span class="mono">K<sub>a</sub> = [H<sup>+</sup>][A<sup>−</sup>]/[HA]</span> and it rearranges to
      <span class="mono">pH = pK<sub>a</sub> + log<sub>10</sub>([A<sup>−</sup>]/[HA]) = {res.pKa_display} + log<sub>10</sub>({res.buffer_ratio_display}) = {res.hh_pH_display}</span>
      — the same value as −log<sub>10</sub>[H<sup>+</sup>]. With equal amounts of acid and base the ratio is 1 and
      <strong>pH = pK<sub>a</sub></strong>. Henderson–Hasselbalch is nothing but mass action, logged.
    </p>
  )}

  <!-- the common-ion effect, the Ksp variant's new move: a pre-loaded shared ion suppresses dissolution (SHOWN + checked) -->
  {isCommonIon && (
    <p class="hhnote">
      <span class="badge machine tiny"><span class="dot"></span>Common-ion effect</span>
      In <strong>pure water</strong> {lesson.reaction.saltPretty} dissolves to <span class="mono">{res.molar_solubility_pure_water_M_display} M</span>.
      Start instead with <strong>{lesson.reaction.common_ion_molarity_M} M {lesson.reaction.commonIonPretty}</strong> already in solution and that shared ion
      hardly moves as the solid dissolves, so <span class="mono">K<sub>sp</sub> = {inQ.map((r) => `[${r.idPretty}]${r.nu > 1 ? (SUP[r.nu] ?? `^${r.nu}`) : ""}`).join("")}</span>
      is satisfied at a far smaller [{inQ[0].idPretty}]. The <strong>same cubic</strong> now gives
      <span class="mono">{xSym} = {res.molar_solubility_M_display} M</span> — about <strong>{res.suppression_factor_display}× less</strong>.
      Le Chatelier: the pre-loaded {lesson.reaction.commonIonPretty} pushes <Fragment set:html={lesson.reaction.latexHtml} /> to the left.
    </p>
  )}

  <!-- polyprotic: the later ionizations, each solved on the previous stage's output (SHOWN + machine-checked) -->
  {isPoly && (
    <div class="stages">
      <div class="proof-head">
        <span class="badge machine"><span class="dot"></span>The later ionizations</span>
        <strong>Each is the same ICE solve — run on what the stage before it left behind.</strong>
      </div>
      <div class="tablewrap">
        <table class="ice laterstages">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Stage</th><th>Equilibrium</th><th class="num">K<sub>a</sub></th>
              <th class="num">extent x</th><th class="num">product formed</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {res.later_stages.map((ls) => (
              <tr>
                <td class="sym">{ls.index}</td>
                <td class="sym"><span set:html={ls.reactantPretty} /> ⇌ H<sup>+</sup> + <span set:html={ls.anionPretty} /></td>
                <td class="num"><span set:html={ls.kaSci} /></td>
                <td class="num"><span set:html={ls.extentSci} /></td>
                <td class="num">[<span set:html={ls.anionPretty} />] = <span set:html={ls.anionEqmSci} /></td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="hhnote">
        <span class="badge machine tiny"><span class="dot"></span>The payoff</span>
        The first ionization gives <strong>[H<sup>+</sup>] = {res.hydronium_M_display} M</strong> ({res.percent_ionization_display}%);
        each later stage adds a vanishing amount. And because [H<sup>+</sup>] ≈ [<span set:html={res.later_stages[0].reactantPretty} />]
        after stage 1, the second stage's K<sub>a</sub> collapses to just its product:
        <span class="mono"> [<span set:html={res.later_stages[0].anionPretty} />] = <span set:html={res.later_stages[0].anionEqmSci} /> M ≈ K<sub>a2</sub> = <span set:html={res.later_stages[0].kaSci} /></span>.
        The fully-stripped <span set:html={res.species_ladder[res.species_ladder.length - 1].idPretty} /> is essentially absent
        (<span set:html={res.species_ladder[res.species_ladder.length - 1].eqmSci} /> M).
      </p>
      <div class="ladder">
        <span class="ladder-label">Every species at equilibrium:</span>
        <span class="ladder-vals">
          {res.species_ladder.map((l, i) => (
            <span class="lv">[<span set:html={l.idPretty} />] = <span set:html={l.eqmSci} /> M{i < res.species_ladder.length - 1 ? " · " : ""}</span>
          ))}
        </span>
      </div>
    </div>
  )}

  <!-- the machine-checked facts, SHOWN not asserted -->
  <div class="proof">
    <div class="proof-head">
      <span class="badge machine"><span class="dot"></span>Verification</span>
      <strong>Proven at build time — not asserted.</strong>
    </div>
    <ul class="checks">
      <li><span class="tick">✓</span> Every equilibrium concentration = initial + ν·{xSym} <span class="tier">[ICE identity]</span></li>
      <li><span class="tick">✓</span> The extent {xSym} re-solved independently — numerically, to high precision — reproduces Q = <Fragment set:html={kHtml} /> <span class="tier">[mass-action root]</span></li>
      <li><span class="tick">✓</span> {isKsp ? "The pure solid is excluded from Q; s > 0" : isBase ? `Water is excluded from Q; 0 < ${xSym} < [${lesson.reaction.basePretty}]₀` : `0 < ${xSym} < [${lesson.reaction.acidPretty}]₀`} — no concentration goes negative <span class="tier">[extent physical]</span></li>
      <li><span class="tick">✓</span> {isKsp ? "solubility (g/L) = s × molar mass" : isBase ? "[H⁺] = K_w/[OH⁻]; pH = −log₁₀[H⁺]; pH + pOH = pK_w" : isBuffer ? "pH = pK_a + log₁₀([A⁻]/[HA]) = −log₁₀[H⁺]" : isTitration ? "every curve point's pH re-derived by its region; pH ≈ pK_a at half-equivalence; equivalence is basic" : "pH = −log₁₀[H⁺]"} <span class="tier">[{isKsp ? "solubility consistent" : isBase ? "K_w bridge" : isBuffer ? "Henderson–Hasselbalch" : isTitration ? "curve re-derived" : "log consistent"}]</span></li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- misconception register -->
  {lesson.misconception && (
    <div class="misconception">
      <div class="mis-claim"><span class="x">✗</span> Common misconception: “<span set:html={lesson.misconception.claimHtml} />”</div>
      <p class="mis-fix">
        {isCommonIon ? (
          <>
            Solubility is <strong>not</strong> a fixed property of the salt — it depends on what is <em>already</em> dissolved.
            The shared {lesson.reaction.commonIonPretty} is a <strong>product</strong> of the dissolution, so (Le Chatelier) it
            drives <Fragment set:html={lesson.reaction.latexHtml} /> back toward the solid. The ledger shows it: with
            {" "}{lesson.reaction.common_ion_molarity_M} M {lesson.reaction.commonIonPretty} present, only
            {" "}<strong>{xSym} = {res.molar_solubility_M_display} M</strong> of {lesson.reaction.saltPretty} dissolves — about
            {" "}<strong>{res.suppression_factor_display}×</strong> less than the {res.molar_solubility_pure_water_M_display} M it
            reaches in pure water. <Fragment set:html={kHtml} /> is unchanged; the <em>solubility</em> is not. That is the
            {" "}<strong>common-ion effect</strong> — the same move that holds a buffer's pH near pK<sub>a</sub>.
          </>
        ) : isKsp ? (
          <>
            Careful with the coefficient. Each {lesson.reaction.saltPretty} releases <strong>two</strong> {inQ[1].idPretty}
            ions, so [{inQ[1].idPretty}] = 2{xSym}, and <Fragment set:html={kHtml} /> = [{inQ[0].idPretty}][{inQ[1].idPretty}]<sup>2</sup>
            = {xSym}·(2{xSym})<sup>2</sup> = 4{xSym}<sup>3</sup> — a <strong>cubic</strong>, not {xSym}<sup>2</sup>. That gives
            {" "}{xSym} = ({kHtml.includes("sp") ? "Ksp" : "K"}/4)<sup>1/3</sup> = <strong>{res.molar_solubility_M_display} M</strong>,
            about {kspSqrtRatio}× larger than √<Fragment set:html={kHtml} /> ≈ {(Math.sqrt(Number(kc.value))).toExponential(1)}. The coefficient
            enters <strong>twice</strong> — as a concentration factor and as an exponent.
          </>
        ) : isBuffer ? (
          <>
            The acetate is <strong>not</strong> a spectator here — it is the acid's <strong>conjugate base</strong>, a
            {" "}<strong>common ion</strong>. Le Chatelier: the pre-loaded {lesson.reaction.conjugateBasePretty ?? "A⁻"} pushes
            {" "}<Fragment set:html={lesson.reaction.latexHtml} /> to the left, so far less acid ionizes. The ledger shows the
            extent is only <strong>{xSym} = {ice.extent_M_display} M</strong> ({res.percent_ionization_display}% ionized) —
            about <strong>{res.suppression_factor_display}×</strong> smaller than the {res.hydronium_no_buffer_M_display} M the acid
            reaches <em>alone</em>. So [H<sup>+</sup>] is that much lower and pH = <strong>{res.pH_display}</strong>, not
            {" "}{res.pH_no_buffer_display}. That is what a buffer does: the reservoir of conjugate base holds the pH near pK<sub>a</sub>.
          </>
        ) : isBase ? (
          <>
            That would be true for a <strong>strong</strong> base like NaOH, which delivers its {inQ.find((r) => r.id === "OH^-")?.idPretty ?? "OH⁻"}
            {" "}completely. But ammonia has no {inQ.find((r) => r.id === "OH^-")?.idPretty ?? "OH⁻"} of its own — it must take one from water, and
            the ledger shows the extent is only <strong>{xSym} = {ice.extent_M_display} M</strong>, just <strong>{res.percent_ionization_display}%</strong>
            {" "}ionized. So [OH<sup>−</sup>] = {res.hydroxide_M_display} M, pOH = {res.pOH_display}, and through K<sub>w</sub> the
            pH = <strong>{res.pH_display}</strong> — not 13.00; the other {reactantRow.equilibrium_M_display} M
            {" "}({(100 - Number(res.percent_ionization_display)).toFixed(2)}%) stays as intact {lesson.reaction.basePretty}. Notice the mirror:
            this base at 0.100 M lands as far <em>above</em> pH 7 as 0.100 M acetic acid (same K) lands below it.
          </>
        ) : isPoly ? (
          <>
            Only the <strong>first</strong> proton comes off appreciably. Because each K<sub>a</sub> is about 10<sup>5</sup>
            smaller than the last, the second ionization barely proceeds (x<sub>2</sub> = <span set:html={res.later_stages[0].extentSci} /> M)
            and the third is vanishing (<span set:html={res.species_ladder[res.species_ladder.length - 1].idPretty} /> ≈
            <span set:html={res.species_ladder[res.species_ladder.length - 1].eqmSci} /> M). So <strong>[H<sup>+</sup>] = {res.hydronium_M_display} M</strong>
            comes almost entirely from stage 1 — the extra protons add nothing measurable, and pH = <strong>{res.pH_display}</strong>,
            not one-third lower. A triprotic acid is not “three times” a monoprotic one; it is one moderately weak acid followed
            by two that essentially do not ionize.
          </>
        ) : isTitration ? (
          <>
            That holds only for a <strong>strong</strong> acid + strong base. Here the acid is <strong>weak</strong>: at
            equivalence every <span set:html={lesson.reaction.acidPretty} /> has been converted to its conjugate base
            {" "}<span set:html={lesson.reaction.conjugateBasePretty} />, which is <em>itself</em> a weak base — it takes a
            proton back from water, releasing OH⁻. So the solution is <strong>basic</strong>: the ledger's weak-base solve
            gives <strong>pH {res.pH_equivalence_display}</strong> at the equivalence point, not 7. A pH of 7 would need the
            product to be a spectator; <span set:html={lesson.reaction.conjugateBasePretty} /> is not one.
          </>
        ) : (
          <>
            That would be true for a <strong>strong</strong> acid, which ionizes completely. But the ledger shows the
            extent is only <strong>{xSym} = {ice.extent_M_display} M</strong> — just <strong>{res.percent_ionization_display}%</strong>
            of the acid ionizes. So [H<sup>+</sup>] = {res.hydronium_M_display} M and pH = <strong>{res.pH_display}</strong>, not
            1.00; the other {reactantRow.equilibrium_M_display} M ({(100 - Number(res.percent_ionization_display)).toFixed(2)}%) stays
            as intact {lesson.reaction.acidPretty} molecules. “Weak” means the equilibrium barely moves off the left.
          </>
        )}
      </p>
    </div>
  )}

  <!-- assumptions, disclosed not discharged (ADR-0003) -->
  <details class="assumptions">
    <summary><span class="badge model"><span class="dot"></span>Modeling assumptions</span> — author-asserted, disclosed not discharged</summary>
    <ul>
      {lesson.assumptions.map((a) => (
        <li><span class={`akind ${a.kind}`}>{a.kind}</span> <span set:html={a.claimHtml} /></li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  </details>
</section>

